<br>
This article is mainly concerned with his addiction to online games, it hardly lays any blame on Everquest, it mentions this was the cause of his addiction, and it asks whether Open ended games such as these are a cause for concern.<br>
<br>
Yet the replies I hear on this board are defensive, calling it a biased report when infact I thought it was a very fair report.<br>
<br>
The man obviously had mental problems, the report clearly talks about his mental condition, even reporting the answers from his psychologist: &quot;depression, seizures and being schizoid.&quot;<br>
<br>
The rest of the peice is unrelated to any game and is more concerned with his life style and the way in which he behaved.<br>
<br>
He did go to extremes, yet the baseline of his addiction I see in many people including myself, I don't consider it dangerous, and I don't consider it an addiction. Yet look from an outsiders point of view and that is exactly what it is.<br>
<br>
Anyone in the end game of EQ is an addict, the sheer number of hours it takes to get there, then the number of hours required to be a part of it are in the extreme bracket, and there are a lot of us about, look at the sheer number on this server, and yet you are all out numbered by the americans.<br>
<br>
I don't blame EQ for this, we each have a mind and we choose or choose not to use it.<br>
<br>
I don't think the article blamed EQ either, the only report it did make on blame was to report that the family were trying to find out more about EQ to see IF a lawsuit could be placed.<br>
